 into the metal, already corroding at the edges from the salt air.\n\nWhen I get back to my cabin, I don't turn on the interior light. The amber glow from the corridor is enough. I can see the cot, the locker, the wall screen that hasn't worked since day two. The ceiling is low enough that if I stood on the cot I could touch it.\n\nI lie down. Stare up. Water droplets form in the same spots every time, following the microscopic imperfections in the metal. They grow until they can't hold anymore, then roll sideways toward the seam where the ceiling meets the wall. I watch three of them make the journey.\n\nThe air tastes like I'm breathing through a filter that needs changing. Metallic. Stale. I pull it in through my nose, push it out through my mouth. Two counts in. Four counts out. It's the only thing I can control down here.\n\nThe mechanical hums shift in pitch. Something in the life support system cycling through its routine. Or maybe the hull adjusting to the pressure. I don't know enough about the engineering to tell the difference, and that's the problem. Every sound could be normal or it could be the thing that kills us, and I have no way to know which.\n\nI close my eyes. Keep counting. Two, four. Two, four. My heartbeat slows to match it.\n\nThen the lights go out.\n\nNot the flicker from before. Complete darkness. The amber emergency strips die all at once, and the mechanical hums cut off mid-cycle.\n\nI'm on my feet before I can think. My hand finds the wall in the black. The metal is still wet, still cold, but now there's something else\u2014a vibration I can feel through my palm. Rhythmic. Deliberate.\n\nFrom somewhere in the corridor, I hear footsteps. Too heavy to be Jax. Moving toward my open door.",
