 got him hired for this. What does he gain by killing us all?\n\nI flip back. Forward. Back again. The pages make a sound like shuffling cards.\n\nMy adrenaline hit in my throat. I swallow and it doesn't go away.\n\nThis stopped being about reputation the moment we lost surface contact. But if I tell the whole truth\u2014if I lay out what I did to Jax, what I know about the systems, who had access when\u2014I'm done. And if I'm done, who manages the fallout? Who keeps the crew from tearing each other apart?\n\nI close the logbook. Set it down next to my hip.\n\nIf I dig deeper and find nothing, I've wasted time we don't have. If I dig deeper and find something, I might make it worse. But keeping quiet while people die\u2014\n\n\"Priya,\" I say. \"I need you to trust me on this. Just a little longer.\"\n\nShe crosses her arms. \"That's what you said about the Jax situation. Right before everything went to hell.\"\n\nI stand up too fast. The chair scrapes. My lower back spasms\u2014I've been sitting hunched for hours.\n\nGuilt sits in my chest like a stone. Control sits right next to it, same weight, same shape. I can't tell them apart anymore.\n\nOne option: investigate quiet. Gather proof. Don't say anything until I know what I'm accusing and who I'm burning. Then say it and let the pieces fall.\n\nThe other option doesn't exist.\n\nI step past Priya into the corridor. Emergency lighting throws my shadow long and doubled against the curve of the wall. Somewhere three sections over, machinery hums\u2014recyclers, pumps, the things that keep us breathing.\n\nThe environmental control room is two corridors away. I'm halfway there when the lights cut out.\n\nTotal dark. The kind that makes you forget which way is up.\n\nThen the emergency strips flicker on\u2014red this time, not white. And through the wall I hear it: the high whine of a pressure seal failing. Section C. Where the sleeping quarters are.\n\nWhere most of the crew is right now.",
