      "content": "The Surface rescue vessel, decompression protocol. My lungs are screaming\u2014not from deprivation anymore but from too much at once. The first clean air feels illegal. I drag it in through my nose and mouth, chest heaving like I've forgotten the rhythm. Mara slumps on the metal bench beside me, chin nearly touching her collarbone. Priya's behind us, strapping monitors around our wrists and calves, fingers shaking hard enough I can feel the tremor through the velcro. When her eyes land on mine, there's something past relief. Something that looks like dread. Across from me, Jax hunches over his clasped hands. Another medic works around him, checking vitals, but Jax doesn't lift my head. His knuckles are bone-white.\n\n\"Captain.\" Priya's whisper cuts. \"We need to start decompression now or we're looking at pulmonary edema.\"\n\nMara's head snaps up. The exhaustion vanishes, replaced by the hard angles I've learned to read. She nods once. Then she looks at me.\n\n\"Elena,\" she says, jaw tight. \"When Jax's family arrives at port, I need you to\u2014\"\n\n\"No.\"\n\nThe word comes out raw. Automatic. The old reflex kicks in\u2014smooth it over, spin the narrative, make it palatable\u2014but there's no camera here. No brand to protect. Just metal and salt air and the truth that I'm done performing.\n\nMara's eyebrow lifts. She doesn't push. Just watches me for three long seconds.\n\n\"Alright,\" she says. \"Then breathe. You've earned that much.\"\n\nPriya circles back to me with an IV kit. The needle glints under the overhead lights\u2014too bright after days in the dark. She swabs my inner elbow, taps the vein.\n\n\"How's Jax?\" I ask.\n\n\"Stable.\" The needle slides in. I don't flinch. \"But he hasn't said more than two words since we left the Aethelgard.\"\n\nMara shifts beside me. Her shoulders drop half an inch.\n\nAbove us, machinery hums. Waves slap the hull in an uneven rhythm that makes my stomach clench. I can't tell if it's nausea or just the memory of pressure.\n\n\"Why do you think\u2014\" I start.\n\n\"Survivor guilt,\" Priya says before I finish. She tapes down the IV line. \"Fear. Shock. Take your pick.\"\n\nMara exhales hard through her nose. \"We should start decompression.\"\n\nI nod. Across from me, Jax's shoulders hitch with each breath. Too fast. Too shallow.\n\n\"Elena?\"\n\nMy voice is barely there. I turn fully toward him, and he lifts her head just enough that I can see his eyes. They're hollow. Older than they were three days ago.\n\n\"We're free,\" he whispers.\n\nI hold my gaze. \"Not yet. But we're safe.\"\n\nIt's not the same thing. He knows it. I know it. The distinction sits between us like a third person on the bench.\n\nMara stands, movements deliberate. \"Alright. Let's begin.\"\n\nPriya finishes with my monitors and follows Mara toward the control station. Screens flicker with readouts I don't understand\u2014depth, pressure, oxygen saturation. The numbers mean something to them. To me they're just proof we're still being measured.\n\nI reach over and rest my hand on Jax's shoulder. He flinches but doesn't pull away.\n\n\"Tell me what happened down there,\" I say quietly.\n\nHe stares at his hands. My throat works.\n\n\"I don't\u2014\" He stops. Starts again. \"I'm not sure I can.\"",
